\subsection{Homotopy Groups}

The \textit{homotopy groups} of a space $X$ are a sequence of abelian groups, denoted by $\pi_n(X)$, that describe the connectivity of the space. They measure the extent to which continuous mappings from a point (or sphere) to $X$ can be deformed into one another. The $0$th homotopy group is equivalent to the fundamental group, while higher homotopy groups capture more intricate structures in the space.

\subsection{Cohomology Rings}

Cohomology is a tool for studying the topological properties of spaces. It is a sequence of abelian groups, denoted by $H^*(X; \mathbb{F})$, where $\mathbb{F}$ is a field (usually the rationals, $\mathbb{Q}$, or the reals, $\mathbb{R}$). The cohomology groups capture the behavior of cochains, which are multilinear maps from the space to the coefficient field.

\subsection{Spectral Sequences}

Spectral sequences are a powerful tool for computing various cohomology groups. They provide a concise way to compute the cohomology of a space by reducing the number of calculations needed in the Mayer-Vietoris sequence. A spectral sequence is generated from a filtration of the cohomology of a space, and it converges to the final cohomology of a related space, such as a quotient or a fiber bundle.

